<h5 class="mt-5">How do I install TypeScript?</h5>

<p>
    Both Visual Studio and Visual Studio code come with TypeScript support built it so you
    may not have to do anything.  But if you do, see below.
</p>

<ol>
    <li>Install Node.js</li>
    <li>
        Once Node.js is installed, type <code>npm install -g typescript</code>.
        This is the node package manager. <code>-g</code> indicates we
        want it installed globally.
    </li>
</ol>

<p>
    To see what version of Node.js is installed, type <code>node -v</code> at a Powershell command prompt.
</p>

<div class="my-3">
    <img src="/assets/images/node-version.PNG" class="d-block mx-auto" />
</div>

<p>Visual Studio Code will tell you which version of ts you are using when you are editing a ts file: </p>

<div class="my-3">
    <img src="/assets/images/vs-code-ts-version.PNG" class="d-block mx-auto" />
</div>

<p>With TypeScript, you get the <code>tsc</code> - the TypeScript compiler.</p>

<h5 class="mt-5">What is tsc?</h5>

<p><code>tsc</code> is the TypeScript compiler and it runs on Node.js which should be installed on your local machine.</p>

<p>
    To run the <code>tsc</code> and to have it build a package/task (such as tsconfig.json), type <code>tsc -p tsconfig.json</code>
    in the root of your project from the command prompt.
</p>

<div class="my-3">
    <img src="/assets/images/tsc-build-example.PNG" class="d-block mx-auto" />
</div>

<p>To run this task in VS Code, just use the shortcut <code>ctrl + shift + B</code>.</p>

<div class="my-3">
    <img src="/assets/images/tsc-build-example.PNG" class="d-block mx-auto" />
</div>

